{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492981"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:52:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:52:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1196"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1196","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1196"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.38,0.08,0.05,0.42,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1196"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41674"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1196","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1196"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1196"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26595"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2512"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2934"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41674","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41674"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old man presents with right iliac fossa pain and subsequently undergoes a laparoscopic appendicectomy for an inflamed appendicitis. Histological examination of the appendix confirms appendicitis as well as the presence of an 8 mm carcinoid tumour at the tip of the appendix with clear margins.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No further investigation or treatment required","Urinary 5-hydroxyindoleacetic acid","Serum chromogranin","CT abdomen","Right hemicolectomy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECarcinoid or neuroendocrine tumours can be found incidentally in up to 2% of appendicectomy specimens. Small (\u0026lt;10mm) carcinoid tumours with clear margins that are found incidentally at the time of appendicectomy \u003Cstrong\u003Edo not need any further treatment or follow-up.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinary 5-hydroxyindoleacetic acid (5HIAA)\u003C/strong\u003E is a serotonin metabolite which may be raised in patients with carcinoid tumours. However, this test should only be used in patients who are symptomatic and is not required especially as the tumour has been surgically removed. \u003Cstrong\u003ESerum chromogranin\u003C/strong\u003E is a carcinoid tumour marker and is usually normal in patients with a tumour size of \u0026lt;2cm. It is not required for the follow up of this patient. \u003Cstrong\u003ECT abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E is not required for this patient due to the tumour size (\u0026lt;10mm) and clear margins. A \u003Cstrong\u003Eright\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Ehemicolectomy\u003C/strong\u003E may be required for patients with more advanced tumours or residual disease. This is not required in this case. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Appendiceal carcinoid tumours that are less than 10mm in size and with clear margins do not require any further follow up or investigations."],"references":["Moris D, Tsilimigras DI, Vagios S, et al. Neuroendocrine Neoplasms of the Appendix: A Review of the Literature. Anticancer Res 2018; 38:601-12. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29374682/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26595"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1196"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions